{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491263","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491263"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:40:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:40:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"895"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"895","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/895"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.81,0.07,0.01,0.05,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"895"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"36486"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"895","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/895"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"895"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"21209"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"570"},{"type":"tags","id":"6002"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7965"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7983"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"36486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/36486"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA young man is brought to the Emergency Department after a fall from a trampoline onto his left arm. He complains of pain in his distal left arm. On examination, he is unable to move the glenohumeral joint or elbow joint because of pain, but is able to flex his wrist. The brachial and radial pulses are strong. Sensation in his arm and hand is intact. An X-ray is performed (Image 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following management approaches is most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Open reduction, internal fixation","External fixation","Forearm brace","Hanging cast","Collar and cuff sling"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe X-rays show a comminuted fracture of the left distal humerus. Distal humerus fractures represent 0.5-7% of all fractures and approximately 30% of fractures above the elbow. They have a bimodal distribution, occuring in young patients with high energy trauma and late in elderly patients with osteoporotic bone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExamination of a distal humerus fracture should include assessment of open wounds, and examination of neurovascular status is critical.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDiagnosis of distal humerus fractures should include radiographical evaluation of anteroposterior, oblique and lateral and views of the elbow joint. Traction views are not used, as they will just cause pain. Additional imaging of the shoulder and wrist is also important with concomitant injuries present in up to 17% of cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EClassification is most commonly based on the Orthopaedic Trauma Association (OTA/AO) system. This divides the distal humerus into two columns (medial and lateral) connected by the trochlea. Restoring this relationship is the goal of treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHistorically, the treatment of distal humerus fractures was predominantly nonoperative. Treatment options included traction, condylar compression, cuff and collar support, closed reduction and casting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENew evidence now suggests that in patients with good bone quality, operative management (\u003Cstrong\u003Eopen reduction and internal fixation\u003C/strong\u003E) is the standard of care with plate osteosynthesis. In elderly patients with osteoporotic bone, there are significant challenges to adequate fixation, and thus nonoperative management or prosthetic elbow replacement should be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EComplications of surgical fixation include infection, nonuinion, post-operative stiffness, heterotopic ossification, ulnar neuritis, osteoarthritis and avascular necrosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Open reduction and internal fixation is the preferred treatment approach for most adults with supracondylar fractures."],"references":["Lauder A, Richard MJ. Management of distal humerus fractures. European Journal of Orthopaedic Surgery \u0026 Traumatology. 2020;30(5):745-62.","Ul Islam S, Glover AW, Waseem M. Challenges and Solutions in Management of Distal Humerus Fractures. Open Orthop J. 2017;11:1292-307."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"21209"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"895"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20018"},{"type":"media","id":"20019"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20018","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20018"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/712dc3c6-5bb0-485e-b68b-02be18f40f31.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/712dc3c6-5bb0-485e-b68b-02be18f40f31.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":337,"height":600}},{"type":"media","id":"20019","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20019"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7fc492e9-f4fe-4445-85d3-46bee65967ab.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7fc492e9-f4fe-4445-85d3-46bee65967ab.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":611,"height":800}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"21209","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/21209"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-05-28T09:49:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2023-05-28T09:49:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"895"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"36486"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://